ocr.sentence: adjici ut lectores integrioris formae admoneantur.
ocr.region: adjici ut lectores integrioris formae admoneantur. Mr θελήσας Isaeus Cir. p.69. $.11. zu} θέλοι Lycurg. Leoer. p. 157, 77. etc. et similia apud Demosthenem, cui Schaeferus μὴ ἐθέλειν eximere studet ad p. 1451, 61. cf. Ruediger ad Philipp. I. p. 27. Thuoydidi familiarius verbum trisyllabum , nee dubita- tione caruit ei θέλοιμεν VI. 34, A. sed Platoni jure reli- quit Schneiderus ad Civ. T. I. p. 230. T. III. p. 15%. etsi apud hunc ut apud ceteros antiquiores praevalet ἐθέλειν. V. 25. Ἐφθαρμένας — Hunc et insequentem versum producit Suidas s. Asius. Verbum κατηναρισμένας ex h. l. idem et Ilesychius et Schol. Ven. XXI. 26. enotarunt. Quod sequitur, ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις, id Suidas s. Ἐπιστάτις in- terpretatur zeig «vol, fortasse ne Ajax caedis verae nec ad vindictam necessariae reus agatur; idemque sensisse videtur gui v. 232. adseripsit: οὗτοι γὰρ ἐνόμιζον καὶ ποιμένας αὐτὸν ἀνῃρηκέναι, id est, solam in hoc conjeciuram sequun- tur. _Rectius Schol. Rom. zoig ποιμέσι· καλῶς δὲ τοῦτο, iva μὴ παραγένοιτό τις ἀπαγγέλλων To σαφές. Sic ποιμ- νίων ἐπιστάταις Plat. Legg. X. 906. A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει. Codd. A. La. Lb. Aug. B. τρέπει, hic supra seripto νέμει. IIlud Valckenarius ad Hipp. p- 306. e,glossa eis αὐτὸν τρέπει ortum putat. Galenus de Plenit. c. XI. 346. T. VII. Chart. p. 582. Kuehn. οὐκ ἴσην ἅπασι νέμει τὴν alviav. V. 29. Keil μοί τις ὀπτήρ- εἰσιδών — haec verba ap- ponit Thomas s. Orryje, lolum versum cum insequenti Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, quam vocem Eustathius p. 788, 31. ex h. |. affert. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα nedie. E Scholiastae interpreta- mento τῷ πεδίῳ nata est codd. nonnullorum lectio πεδίῳ. Syntaxis hujus exempla abunde multa extant, sed regula parum claret; πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην lesai. XVI. 8. πολ- λὴν ἐρημίαν Conon. Narr. II. πολλὴν γῆν Xenoph. Eph. V. 14, 116. Plutarch. Lucull. e. XXXIV. cf. Aglaoph. T. I. 49. πολὺν πλανᾷσθαι τόπον Dio Chr. VII. 226. πᾶσαν πλανηθεὶς χθόνα Eur. Hel. 598. γῆν ἀπίαν ἀλώμενος Oed. C. 1686: τὴν πλανοστιβῆ γῆν Beßus Aesch. Eum. 76.

Leoer. p. 157, 77. etc. et similia apud Demosthenem, cui Schaeferus μὴ ἐθέλειν eximere studet ad p. 1451, 61. cf. Ruediger ad Philipp. I. p. 27. Thuoydidi familiarius verbum trisyllabum , nee dubita- tione caruit ei θέλοιμεν VI. 34, A. sed Platoni jure reli- quit Schneiderus ad Civ. T. I. p. 230. T. III. p. 15%. etsi apud hunc ut apud ceteros antiquiores praevalet ἐθέλειν. V. 25. Ἐφθαρμένας — Hunc et insequentem versum producit Suidas s. Asius. Verbum κατηναρισμένας ex h. l. idem et Ilesychius et Schol. Ven. XXI. 26. enotarunt. Quod sequitur, ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις, id Suidas s. Ἐπιστάτις in- terpretatur zeig «vol, fortasse ne Ajax caedis verae nec ad vindictam necessariae reus agatur; idemque sensisse videtur gui v. 232. adseripsit: οὗτοι γὰρ ἐνόμιζον καὶ ποιμένας αὐτὸν ἀνῃρηκέναι, id est, solam in hoc conjeciuram sequun- tur. _Rectius Schol. Rom. zoig ποιμέσι· καλῶς δὲ τοῦτο, iva μὴ παραγένοιτό τις ἀπαγγέλλων To σαφές. Sic ποιμ- νίων ἐπιστάταις Plat. Legg. X. 906. A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει. Codd. A. La. Lb. Aug. B. τρέπει, hic supra seripto νέμει. IIlud Valckenarius ad Hipp. p- 306. e,glossa eis αὐτὸν τρέπει ortum putat. Galenus de Plenit. c. XI. 346. T. VII. Chart. p. 582. Kuehn. οὐκ ἴσην ἅπασι νέμει τὴν alviav. V. 29. Keil μοί τις ὀπτήρ- εἰσιδών — haec verba ap- ponit Thomas s. Orryje, lolum versum cum insequenti Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, quam vocem Eustathius p. 788, 31. ex h. |. affert. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα nedie. E Scholiastae interpreta- mento τῷ πεδίῳ nata est codd. nonnullorum lectio πεδίῳ. Syntaxis hujus exempla abunde multa extant, sed regula parum claret; πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην lesai. XVI. 8. πολ- λὴν ἐρημίαν Conon. Narr. II. πολλὴν γῆν Xenoph. Eph. V. 14, 116. Plutarch. Lucull. e. Thucydidi familiarius verbum trisyllabum, nec dubita- tione caruit εἰ θέλοιμεν Vl. 34, ⟨. sed Platoni jure reli- quit Schneiderus ad Civ. T. I. p. 230. T. III. p. 154. etsi apud hunc ut apud ceteros antiquiores praevalet ἐθέλειν. V. 25. Ἐφθαρμένας - Hunc et insequentem versum producit Suidas s. Λείας. Verbum κατηναρισμένας ex h. l. idem et Hesychius et Schol. Ven. XXI. 26. enotarunt. Quod sequitur, ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις, id Suidas s. Ἐπιστάτις in- terpretatur τοῖς κυσί, fortasse ne Ajax caedis verae nec ad vindictam necessariae reus agatur ; idemque sensisse videtur qui v. 232. adscripsit : οὗτοι γὰρ ἐνόμιζον καὶ ποιμένας αὐτὸν ἀνῃρηκέναι, id est, solam in hoc conjecturam sequun- tur. Rectius Schol. Rom. τοῖς ποιμέσι· καλῶς δὲ τοῦτο, ἵνα μὴ παραγένοιτό τις ἀπαγγέλλων τὸ σαφές. Sic ποιμ- νίων ἐπιστάταις Plat. Legg. X. 906. A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει. Codd. Δ. La. Lb. Aug. B. τρέπει, hic supra scripto νέμει. Illud Valckenarius ad Hipp. p. 306. e glossa εἰς αὐτὸν τρέπει ortum putat. Galenus de Plenit. c. Xl. 346. T. VII. Chart. p. 582. Kuehn. οὐκ ἴσην ἅπασι νέμει τὴν αἰτίαν. V. 29. Καί μοί τις ὀπτήρ - εἰςιδών - haec verba ap- ponit Thomas s. Ὀπτήρ, totum versum cum insequenti Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, quam vocem Eustathius p. 788, 31. ex h. l. affert. ED. PR. V. 30 Πηδῶντα πεδία. E Scholiastae interpreta- mento τῷ πεδίῳ nata est codd. nonnullorum lectio πεδίῳ. Syntaxis hujus exempla abunde multa extant, sed regula parum claret ; πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην Iesai. XVI. 8. πολ- λήν ἐρημίαν Conon. Narr. II. πολλὴν γῆν Xenoph. Eph. V. 14, 116. Plutarch. Lucull. c. XXXIV. cf. Aglaoph. T. I. 49. πολὺν πλανᾶσθαι τόπον Dio Chr. VII. 226. πᾶσαν πλανηθεὶς χθόνα Eur. Hel. 598. γῆν ἀπίαν ἀλώμενος 0ed. C. 1686. τὴν πλανοστιβῆ γῆν βεβώς Aesch, Eum. 76.

INTRODUCTION:
Introduction: Introduction to an exam (a book in the same series as the test) is a series of sentences that have to be followed by a number of sentences that address each sentence in a different way. The test is organized in the following way: first of all the question is presented, followed by the sentence to answer in which the question is introduced. The test can be used for the purpose of reading or composition (reading, writing) exams. For this purpose, the exam is divided into four parts, the question part, the answer part, the test part and the answer part. The answer part consists of only two sentences. For the question part, you must follow the sentences

Leoer. p. 157, 77. etc. et similia apud Demosthenem, cui Schaeferus μὴ ἐθέλειν eximere studet ad p. 1451, 61. cf. Ruediger ad Philipp. I. p. 27. Thuoydidi familiarius verbum trisyllabum , nee dubita- tione caruit ei θέλοιμεν VI. 34, A. sed Platoni jure reli- quit Schneiderus ad Civ. T. I. p. 230. T. III. p. 15%. etsi apud hunc ut apud ceteros antiquiores praevalet ἐθέλειν. V. 25. Ἐφθαρμένας — Hunc et insequentem versum producit Suidas s. Asius. Verbum κατηναρισμένας ex h. l. idem et Ilesychius et Schol. Ven. XXI. 26. enotarunt. Quod sequitur, ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις, id Suidas s. Ἐπιστάτις in- terpretatur zeig «vol, fortasse ne Ajax caedis verae nec ad vindictam necessariae reus agatur; idemque sensisse videtur gui v. 232. adseripsit: οὗτοι γὰρ ἐνόμιζον καὶ ποιμένας αὐτὸν ἀνῃρηκέναι, id est, solam in hoc conjeciuram sequun- tur. _Rectius Schol. Rom. zoig ποιμέσι· καλῶς δὲ τοῦτο, iva μὴ παραγένοιτό τις ἀπαγγέλλων To σαφές. Sic ποιμ- νίων ἐπιστάταις Plat. Legg. X. 906. A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει. Codd. A. La. Lb. Aug. B. τρέπει, hic supra seripto νέμει. IIlud Valckenarius ad Hipp. p- 306. e,glossa eis αὐτὸν τρέπει ortum putat. Galenus de Plenit. c. XI. 346. T. VII. Chart. p. 582. Kuehn. οὐκ ἴσην ἅπασι νέμει τὴν alviav. V. 29. Keil μοί τις ὀπτήρ- εἰσιδών — haec verba ap- ponit Thomas s. Orryje, lolum versum cum insequenti Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, quam vocem Eustathius p. 788, 31. ex h. |. affert. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα nedie. E Scholiastae interpreta- mento τῷ πεδίῳ nata est codd. nonnullorum lectio πεδίῳ. Syntaxis hujus exempla abunde multa extant, sed regula parum claret; πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην lesai. XVI. 8. πολ- λὴν ἐρημίαν Conon. Narr. II. πολλὴν γῆν Xenoph. Eph. V. 14, 116. Plutarch. Lucull. e. XXXIV. cf. Aglaoph. T. I. 49. πολὺν πλανᾷσθαι τόπον Dio Chr. VII. 226. πᾶσαν πλανηθεὶς χθόνα Eur. Hel. 598. γῆν ἀπίαν ἀλώμενος Oed. C. 1686: τὴν πλανοστιβῆ γῆν Beßus Aesch. Eum. 76.

Thuoydidi familiarius verbum trisyllabum , nee dubita- tione caruit ei θέλοιμεν VI. 34, A. sed Platoni jure reli- quit Schneiderus ad Civ. T. I. p. 230. T. III. p. 15%. etsi apud hunc ut apud ceteros antiquiores praevalet ἐθέλειν. V. 25. Ἐφθαρμένας — Hunc et insequentem versum producit Suidas s. Asius. Verbum κατηναρισμένας ex h. l. idem et Ilesychius et Schol. Ven. XXI. 26. enotarunt. Quod sequitur, ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις, id Suidas s. Ἐπιστάτις in- terpretatur zeig «vol, fortasse ne Ajax caedis verae nec ad vindictam necessariae reus agatur; idemque sensisse videtur gui v. 232. adseripsit: οὗτοι γὰρ ἐνόμιζον καὶ ποιμένας αὐτὸν ἀνῃρηκέναι, id est, solam in hoc conjeciuram sequun- tur. _Rectius Schol. Rom. zoig ποιμέσι· καλῶς δὲ τοῦτο, iva μὴ παραγένοιτό τις ἀπαγγέλλων To σαφές. Sic ποιμ- νίων ἐπιστάταις Plat. Legg. X. 906. A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει. Codd. A. La. Lb. Aug. B. τρέπει, hic supra seripto νέμει. IIlud Valckenarius ad Hipp. p- 306. e,glossa eis αὐτὸν τρέπει ortum putat. Galenus de Plenit. c. XI. 346. T. VII. Chart. p. 582. Kuehn. οὐκ ἴσην ἅπασι νέμει τὴν alviav. V. 29. Keil μοί τις ὀπτήρ- εἰσιδών — haec verba ap- ponit Thomas s. Orryje, lolum versum cum insequenti Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, quam vocem Eustathius p. 788, 31. ex h. |. affert. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα nedie. E Scholiastae interpreta- mento τῷ πεδίῳ nata est codd. nonnullorum lectio πεδίῳ. Syntaxis hujus exempla abunde multa extant, sed regula parum claret; πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην lesai. XVI. 8. πολ- λὴν ἐρημίαν Conon. Narr. II. πολλὴν γῆν Xenoph. Eph. V. 14, 116. Plutarch. Lucull. e. XXXIV. cf. Aglaoph. T. I. 49. πολὺν πλανᾷσθαι τόπον Dio Chr. VII. 226. πᾶσαν πλανηθεὶς χθόνα Eur. Hel. 598. γῆν ἀπίαν ἀλώμενος Oed. C. 1686: τὴν πλανοστιβῆ γῆν Beßus Aesch. Eum. 76.

Ὀπτῆρας, quam vocem Eustathius p. 788, 31. ex h. |. affert. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα nedie. E Scholiastae interpreta- mento τῷ πεδίῳ nata est codd. nonnullorum lectio πεδίῳ. Leoer. p. 157, 77. etc. et similia apud Demosthenem, cui Schaeferus μὴ ἐθέλειν eximere studet ad p. 1451, 61. cf. Ruediger ad Philipp. I. p. 27. Thuoydidi familiarius verbum trisyllabum , nee dubita- tione caruit ei θέλοιμεν VI. 34, A. sed Platoni jure reli- quit Schneiderus ad Civ. T. I. p. 230. T. III. p. 15%. etsi apud hunc ut apud ceteros antiquiores praevalet ἐθέλειν. V. 25. Ἐφθαρμένας — Hunc et insequentem versum producit Suidas s. Asius. Verbum κατηναρισμένας ex h. l. idem et Ilesychius et Schol. Ven. XXI. 26. enotarunt. Quod sequitur, ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις, id Suidas s. Ἐπιστάτις in- terpretatur zeig «vol, fortasse ne Ajax caedis verae nec ad vindictam necessariae reus agatur; idemque sensisse videtur gui v. 232. adseripsit: οὗτοι γὰρ ἐνόμιζον καὶ ποιμένας αὐτὸν ἀνῃρηκέναι, id est, solam in hoc conjeciuram sequun- tur. _Rectius Schol. Rom. zoig ποιμέσι· καλῶς δὲ τοῦτο, iva μὴ παραγένοιτό τις ἀπαγγέλλων To σαφές. Sic ποιμ- νίων ἐπιστάταις Plat. Legg. X. 906. A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει. Codd. A. La. Lb. Aug. B. τρέπει, hic supra seripto νέμει. IIlud Valckenarius ad Hipp. p- 306. e,glossa eis αὐτὸν τρέπει ortum putat. Galenus de Plenit. c. XI. 346. T. VII. Chart. p. 582. Kuehn. οὐκ ἴσην ἅπασι νέμει τὴν alviav. V. 29. Keil μοί τις ὀπτήρ- εἰσιδών — haec verba ap- ponit Thomas s. Orryje, lolum versum cum insequenti Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, quam vocem Eustathius p. 788, 31. ex h. |. affert. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα nedie. E Scholiastae interpreta- mento τῷ πεδίῳ nata est codd. nonnullorum lectio πεδίῳ. Syntaxis hujus exempla abunde multa extant, sed regula parum claret; πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην lesai. XVI. 8. πολ- λὴν ἐρημίαν Conon. Narr. II. πολλὴν γῆν Xenoph. Eph. V. 14, 116. Plutarch. Lucull. e. XXXIV. cf. Aglaoph. T. I. 49. πολὺν πλανᾷσθαι τόπον Dio Chr. VII. 226. πᾶσαν πλανηθεὶς χθόνα Eur. Hel. 598. γῆν ἀπίαν ἀλώμενος Oed. C. 1686: τὴν πλανοστιβῆ γῆν Beßus Aesch. Eum. 76.

CONCLUSIONS
This article describes how the authors used the system of sentence correction to produce a set of documents that included two types of historical documents, namely, commentary, written text. For a single sentence, each commentary and document were analyzed, which resulted in a sentence-to-correct set. The results are discussed in terms of the linguistic features that are common to the two types of documents and the errors found.
The main feature that distinguishes the two types of documents is that the same sentences and words are written by the two different authors of a single commentary

THE MINE OF THE DAY
A. A. GRIFFITH: The Great Pioneer.




THE MINE OF THE DAY

BY A. A. GRIFFITH.


The scene from which the poem is based is, of course, the great Pioneer, the Emperor Napoleon III. At the time of the Pioneer, Europe was still an empire under Britain. The British monarch had already seized a large part of Italy, and an army was already in preparation for an invasion of Germany, who, with the help of the French, had invaded Germany. The Emperor Napoleon III. had been, in that time, a man of rare power and extraordinary genius.

712.


THE MINE OF THE DAY
A. A. GRIFFITH: The Great Pioneer.




THE MINE OF THE DAY

BY A. A. GRIFFITH.


The scene from which the poem is based is, of course, the great Pioneer, the Emperor Napoleon III. At the time of the Pioneer, Europe was still an empire under Britain. The British monarch had already seized a large part of Italy, and an army was already in preparation for an invasion of Germany, who, with the help of the French, had invaded Germany. The Emperor Napoleon III. had been, in that time, a man of rare power and extraordinary genius.

ocr.sentence: 34 Zephyrum dicit in plantas nutricium exercere.
ocr.region: πνεύματος ἐπιρροῆῇ ἀέρα ὑγρὸν ἕλκοντες ὥσπερ νήπιοι παῖδες. Pliny H. M. 18. 34 Zephyrum dicit in plantas nutricium exercere. Lucian Bis accus. § 1 rods ἀνέ- μους purovpyowras. We might add Catull. 62. 39 ut flos.. | Quem mulcent aurae, firmat sol, educat imber.—va ψυχὴν ἀτάλλων. Cp. Tr. 144 τὸ γὰρ νεάζον ἐν τοιοῖσδε βόσκεται| χώροισιν αὐ- τοῦ εἰς. (n.). The word ἀτάλλω (which in Il. 13. 27 means ‘to gambol’) bears the sense of ‘cherishing’ in Hom. epigr. 4. 2 νήπιον αἰδοίης ἐπὶ γούνασι μητρὸς ἀτάλλων, and Pind. fr. 214 γλυκεῖά ol καρδίαν drd\oira... | ἐλπίς. The Homeric form in this sense is ἀτιτάλλω, Od. 18. 323 παῖδα ds ἀτίταλλε. The word drdMw may have been sug- gested to Sophocles by a trait in the scene between Hector and Andromachè: II. 6. 400 παῖδ’ ἐπὶ κόλπῳ ἔχουσ’ ἀταλά- φρονα, νήπιον atrws. χαρμονήν might be acc. in appos. with ψυχὴν only; but is better taken as acc. in agpos. with the whole sentence (see on El 130 ἤκετ’ ἐμῶν καμάτων wapa- utio).—The conjecture χαρμονή is no gain. 880 It is strange that exception should have been taken to the parenthetic οἶδα, which is not rare; cp. 938, O. C. 1615, El. 334. — obros.. p: cp. 83, 421.

At the time Tyrrhener was not a well-born soldier but his family was in the midst of trouble and he was being held prisoner. The soldiers that the army sent to capture Tyrrhener were under the command of the younger brother of the Emperor Lucius (who was also a soldier).
